# Metric Server

The Kubernetes Metrics Server is a cluster add-on that collects CPU and memory usage data from all nodes and pods, exposing these metrics through the Kubernetes API. It is a crucial component for enabling built-in autoscaling features like the Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) and Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA), and for using the kubectl top command. 

Deploy metrric server
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml

The kubectl top command is used to display the resource (CPU/memory) usage of nodes and pods in a Kubernetes cluster. This command requires the Metrics Server to be installed and running in your cluster
kubectl top node
kubectl top node <node_name>
kubectl top pod --all-namespaces
kubectl top pod <pod_name> --namespace=<namespace_name>
kubectl top pod --sort-by=cpu
# or
kubectl top pod --sort-by=memory
kubectl top pod <pod_name> --containers
kubectl top pod -l app=nginx

View only the top 5 CPU-consuming pods:
kubectl top pod --sort-by=cpu | head -n 6 # use '6' to include the header row

The kubectl logs command is the primary tool for viewing the standard output (stdout) and standard error (stderr) streams of containers in a Kubernetes pod. It is essential for real-time debugging and troubleshooting applications within a Kubernetes cluster.

--Specify container name for multi containers pod
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container-name>



